Splitting the data into 70% train and 30% test as well as Scaling the data.

set.seed(12345)
train_ind <- sample(1:nrow(BH),as.integer(nrow(BH)*0.7),replace=FALSE)
BH.train<-BH[train_ind,]
BH.test<-BH[-train_ind,]
BH.train.scal<-scale(BH.train)
sd.train<-rep(0,12)
mean.train<-rep(0,12)
BH.test.scal<-BH.test
for(i in 1:12){
sd.train[i]<-sd(BH.train[,i])
mean.train[i]<-mean(BH.train[,i])
BH.test.scal[,i]<-(BH.test[,i]-mean.train[i])/sd.train[i]
}

performing PCA on Training set

PCA.train<-prcomp(BH.train.scal,center = TRUE,scale. = TRUE)
summary(PCA.train)

Calculating Porportion of Variance explained by each Principal Component

pve<-PCA.train$sdev^2/sum(PCA.train$sdev^2)
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(pve,xlab="Principal Component",ylab="Proportion of Variance Explained",ylim=c(0,1),
type="b")
plot(cumsum(pve),xlab="Principal Component",ylab="Cumsum Proportion of Variance Explained",ylim=c(0,1),
type="b")

cumsum(pve)
##  [1] 0.4978276 0.6287033 0.7219092 0.7891990 0.8454749 0.8858925 0.9190949
##  [8] 0.9398478 0.9574013 0.9733417 0.9881587 1.0000000

From the cumsum(pve) plot, there is no obvious elbow to help identifying number of PCs to retain. We pick the first 5 principal components, which cover about 85% of total variance explained.

Biplot of PC2 vs.PC1

biplot(PCA.train,choices=c(1,2),scale=0,cex=0.6,col=c(8,1))

Based on the Biplot of PC2 vs.PC1, PC1 covers a lot of the correlated census variables. Since they are highly correlated, we can say PC1 is the general census component. PC2 focuses more on the education level, income level, average house size and location of the community. We can call PC2 economic status component.

Biplot of PC3 vs.PC1

biplot(PCA.train,choices=c(1,3),scale=0,cex=0.6,col=c(8,1))

PC3 is clearly focuses on crime rate, racial demographics and tax.

Biplot of PC4 vs.PC1

biplot(PCA.train,choices=c(1,4),scale=0,cex=0.6,col=c(8,1))

PC4 focuses on the education status.

Biplot of PC5 vs.PC1

biplot(PCA.train,choices=c(1,5),scale=0,cex=0.6,col=c(8,1))

Again, PC5 focuses on crime and racial demographics similar to PC3.

Train Test Validation

Lets first take a look at the square of the correlation between original data and data calculated using the matrix multiplication of loading and scores of the first 5 PCs. In other word, lets look at r square. We can compare the R^2 between train and test data.

PCA.test<-predict(PCA.train,newdata=BH.test.scal)
## comparison of correlation
cor.train<-round(cor(as.vector(BH.train.scal),
as.vector(PCA.train$x[,1:5]%*%t(PCA.train$rotation)[1:5,]))^2,2)
cor.test<-round(cor(as.vector(scale(BH.test.scal)),
as.vector(PCA.test[,1:5]%*%t(PCA.train$rotation)[1:5,]))^2,2)

rbind(R.Square.Train=cor.train,R.Square.Test=cor.test)
##                [,1]
## R.Square.Train 0.85
## R.Square.Test  0.81

The we can compare the proportion of varaince explained.

ve<-c(var(PCA.test[,1]),var(PCA.test[,2]),var(PCA.test[,3]),
var(PCA.test[,4]),var(PCA.test[,5]),var(PCA.test[,6]),
var(PCA.test[,7]),var(PCA.test[,8]),var(PCA.test[,9]),var(PCA.test[,10]),
var(PCA.test[,11]),var(PCA.test[,12]))

ve.total<-sum(ve)
pve.test<-sort(ve,decreasing = TRUE)/ve.total
per.diff<- abs(pve-pve.test)/pve
rbind(PVE.Train=pve, PVE.TEST=pve.test, Percent.Diff=per.diff)

Biplot of PC2 vs.PC1

biplot(PCA.train$x,rotated.loading$loadings[,c(1,2)],cex=0.6,col=c(8,1))

Based on the rotated loading plot, it is clear that economic status variables (LSTAT, MEDV) have the most impact on PC2 and PC1 is largely impacted by all of the other census variables. With or without rotation, PC2 is a clear indicator of economic (Income) status.

Biplot of PC3 vs.PC1

biplot(PCA.train$x,rotated.loading$loadings[,c(1,3)],cex=0.6,col=c(8,1))

Similar to pre-rotation plot, PC3 focuses on crime rate and property tax, which implies that PC3 is a good indicator on crimes and tax.

After applying PCA on the numerical variables of Boston Housing data set, we are able to reduce the number of components from 12 to 5. Although the first principal component clustered many correlated census data, we can still exact useful insights on PC2, PC3 and PC4. The use of PCA on this dataset is a success.
